  "stem": "<p class=\"stem_paragraph \">The equation above can be used to calculate the distance <span class=\"italic\">d</span>, in miles, traveled by a car moving at a speed of 55&nbsp;miles per hour over a period of <span class=\"italic\">t</span> hours. For any positive constant <span class=\"italic\">k</span>, the distance the car would have traveled after <span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"9 k\"></span> hours is how many times the distance the car would have traveled after <span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"3 k\"></span>&nbsp;hours?</p>\n",
